{"title_page": "Phil Vickery (rugby union)", "text_new": "{{Other people|Phil Vickery}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2012}}\n{{more footnotes|date=February 2009}}\n{{Infobox rugby biography \n| name = Phil Vickery\n| image = Phil Vickery.JPG\n| birth_name = Philip John Vickery\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1976|3|14|df=yes}}<ref>{{cite news |title=Phil Vickery, the Raging Bull ready to rumble |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1566688/Phil-Vickery-the-Raging-Bull-ready-to-rumble.html |accessdate=7 March 2020 |date=18 October 2007}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Barnstaple]], [[Devon]], [[England]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| height = 6 ft 3 in (1.90 m)\n| weight = 19 st 10 lb (125 kg, 275 lb)\n| girlfriend = \n| ru_position = [[Prop (rugby union)|Prop]]\n| ru_amateuryears = \n| ru_amateurclubs = \n| ru_amupdate =\n| ru_nationalteam = [[England national rugby union team|England]] <br />[[British and Irish Lions]]\n| ru_nationalyears = 1998\u20132010<br />[[2001 British and Irish Lions tour to Australia|2001]], [[2009 British and Irish Lions tour to South Africa|2009]]\n| ru_nationalcaps = 73<br />5\n| ru_nationalpoints = (10)<br />(0)\n| ru_ntupdate = 14 July 2009\n| ru_clubyears = 1995\u20132006<br />2006\u20132010\n| ru_proclubs = {{nobreak|[[Gloucester Rugby]]<br />[[Wasps RFC|London Wasps]]}}\n| ru_clubcaps = 145 <br /> 54\n| ru_clubpoints = (20) <br /> (5)\n| ru_clubupdate = 14 Dec 2010\n| ru_currentclub =\n| ru_province =\n| ru_provinceyears =\n| ru_provincecaps =\n| ru_provincepoints =\n| ru_provinceupdate =\n| ru_sevensnationalyears = \n| ru_sevensnationalteam = \n| ru_sevensnationalcaps =\n| ru_sevensnationalpoints =\n| ru_sevensupdate = \n| ru_coachclubs =\n| ru_coachyears =\n| ru_coachupdate =\n| other = \n| occupation = \n| family = \n| spouse = \n| children = \n| relatives = \n| school = \n| university = \n}}\n\n'''Philip John Vickery''' [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]] [[Deputy Lieutenant|DL]] (born 14 March 1976) is a former English rugby union [[Prop (rugby union)|tighthead prop]] and member of the [[England national rugby union team|England squad]].  He was a member of England's [[2003 Rugby Union World Cup|World Cup]] winning squad in 2003, playing in all seven matches in the tournament, and is a former England captain.  Vickery ended his club rugby career at [[Wasps RFC|London Wasps]], joining the London side in 2006 after eleven years with [[Gloucester Rugby]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guinnesspremiership.com/news/1712.php|title=News - Official Aviva Premiership Website : Post match reaction Saracens v Harlequins|work=guinnesspremiership.com}}{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>  Given the nickname \"Raging Bull\", he played in three Rugby World Cups, including as England captain in the [[2007 Rugby Union World Cup|2007 tournament]], and toured Australia and South Africa with the [[British and Irish Lions]].\n\n==Early years==\nThe son of a dairy farmer, Vickery was born to [[Cornish people|Cornish]] parents in [[Barnstaple]], [[Devon]], England and says he is proud to be a Cornishman and an [[English people|Englishman]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Phil Vickery: The long journey from farm boy to world champion |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/rugby/rugby-union/phil-vickery-the-long-journey-from-farm-boy-to-world-champion-76362.html |accessdate=7 March 2020 |work=The Independent |date=31 January 2004 |language=en}}</ref> Educated at Budehaven School, his interest in sport developed as a youngster, and by age 12 he started playing rugby.  By the age of 16 he gained his first National Representative honour, being picked for the England Schools U16s group.\n\nVickery left school age 16 and worked as a herdsman on his parents' farm.  He remains a qualified cattle inseminator.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2009/mar/14/england-france-phil-vickery-six-nations-preview|title=Rugby union: Interview: Phil Vickery tells Robert Kitson why he is still hungry for England success|author=Robert Kitson|work=the Guardian}}</ref>\n\nVickery has an Oriental [[tattoo]] on his left shoulder which roughly translates to \"''I'll fight you to the death''\", and a bulldog tattoo on his right.\n\n==Career==\nHe started with the Cornish club [[Bude RFC|Bude]], then moved to [[Redruth RFC|Redruth]], during which time he first appeared in an England Colts side.<ref>[http://www.rfu.com/2007/follow-england/profiles/phil-vickery.html  RFU profile] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081003011613/http://www.rfu.com/2007/follow-england/profiles/phil-vickery.html |date=3 October 2008 }}</ref> In 1995, England 'A' coach Richard Hill persuaded the 19-year-old Vickery to join [[Gloucester R.F.C.|Gloucester Rugby]], where he became known as \"The Raging Bull\". Whilst at Gloucester he started in the [[2001\u201302 English Premiership (rugby union)|2002 Zurich Championship Final]] (the year before winning the play-offs constituted winning the English title) in which Gloucester defeated [[Bristol Rugby]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/english/2033061.stm|title=Clockwatch: Bristol v Gloucester |publisher=BBC|date=8 June 2002 |accessdate=8 February 2018}}</ref> The following year he missed their [[2002\u201303 Powergen Cup|2003 Powergen Cup Final]] triumph through injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2003/apr/07/rugbyunion.gloucesterrugby|title=Gloucester given hope by cup win amid financial ruins |publisher=The Guardian|date=7 April 2003|accessdate=8 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/international/2797893.stm|title=Vickery out for season |publisher=BBC |date=25 February 2003|accessdate=9 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nHis representative career went from strength to strength, with appearances for England U21s and Colts in the 1996\u201397 season.\n\nIn April 2006 he announced he was quitting [[Gloucester R.F.C.|Gloucester Rugby]] after 11 years<ref>{{cite web|title=Vickery heads for Gloucester exit|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/rugby_union/english/4921714.stm|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=7 May 2015|date=21 April 2006}}</ref> and signed for [[Wasps RFC|Wasps]] in a 3-year deal.<ref>{{cite web|title=Prop Vickery seals move to Wasps|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/rugby_union/english/4942682.stm|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=7 May 2015|date=26 April 2006}}</ref> Vickery made his [[Wasps RFC|Wasps]] debut in their 23 \u2013 13 win over [[London Irish]] on 8 October 2006. With Wasps he won both the [[Heineken Cup]] in 2007<ref name=\"Heineken Cup final: Leicester 9-25 Wasps\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/6663245.stm|title=Heineken Cup final: Leicester 9\u201325 Wasps|publisher=BBC|date=19 May 2007|accessdate=6 February 2020}}</ref> and the 2008 [[Guinness Premiership]] title.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/7426519.stm |title=Guinness Premiership final |publisher=BBC|date=31 May 2008 |accessdate=6 February 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn 28 October 2010, Vickery was forced to retire from rugby after suffering from several neck injuries.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rees|first1=Paul|title=Phil Vickery calls time on playing career|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2010/oct/28/phil-vickery-to-retire|website=The Guardian|publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited|accessdate=7 May 2015|date=28 October 2010}}</ref> He played his last game at Kingsholm against Gloucester on 25 September, which is where he started his career.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/rugbyunion/international/england/8094577/England-manager-Martin-Johnson-pays-tribute-to-Phil-Vickery.html|title=England manager Martin Johnson pays tribute to Phil Vickery |date=28 October 2010|work=Telegraph|accessdate=2010-10-28}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 May 2012 Worcester Warriors announced that Vickery would join the Club as their new Assistant Forwards (Scrum) coach for the\nforthcoming 2012-2013 season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Phil Vickery joining Premiership club Worcester as a forwards coach|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2012/may/28/phil-vickery-joining-worcester|website=The Guardian|publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited|accessdate=7 May 2015|date=29 May 2012}}</ref> After an unsuccessful season, Worcester made wholesale changes in the coaching staff, from head coach through the assistants, and Vickery was one of the casualties.<ref>{{cite web|title=Worcester Warriors and Nigel Redman part company|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/rugby-union/22487723|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=7 May 2015|date=10 May 2013|quote=World Cup-winning prop Phil Vickery, brought in last summer in a consultancy role, has also left Sixways}}</ref>\n\n==Representative career==\nVickery made his England debut against Wales aged 21 on 21 February 1998, coming off the bench to replace [[Darren Garforth]] against Wales at Twickenham in the Five Nations tournament, a match England won 60\u201326.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/international/2784355.stm|title=BBC SPORT - Rugby Union - Internationals - Wales searching for miracles|work=bbc.co.uk}}</ref> It was the completion of a rapid rise through the England set-up, after only 34 first team games for his club and just 81 days after his England A debut.\n\n'''The Tour from Hell'''\n\nSummer 1998 saw Vickery taking part in the [[1998 England rugby union tour of Australasia and South Africa|tour of the Southern Hemisphere]], part of an England squad which had been severely weakened by injury and player unavailability.  In the space of a month, England were soundly defeated by [[Australia national rugby union team|Australia]] (76\u20130 in Brisbane on 6 June), twice by [[New Zealand national rugby union team|New Zealand]] (64\u201322 in Dunedin on 20 June and 40\u201310 in Auckland on 27 June) and finally by [[South Africa national rugby union team|South Africa]] (18\u20130 in Cape Town on 4 July).  There were also losses to New Zealand 'A', New Zealand Rugby Academy, and [[New Zealand M\u0101ori rugby union team|New Zealand M\u0101ori]].\n\nThe tour had benefits for some players, bringing through future stars of the England side such as Vickery himself, [[Jonny Wilkinson]], [[Danny Grewcock]], [[Graham Rowntree]], [[Austin Healey]], [[Matt Dawson]] and [[Matt Perry (rugby union)|Matt Perry]], others effectively had their international careers ended.  [[Steve Ravenscroft]], Rob Fidler, [[Jos Baxendell]], [[Spencer Brown (rugby player born 1973)|Spencer Brown]] and [[Tom Beim]] each gained two caps on the tour \u2013 and have not played for England since.  Richard Pool-Jones, Scott Benton, Dominic Chapman and [[Stuart Potter]] only played once for England, on the Tour From Hell.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/rugby_union/article825132.ece|title=Login|work=timesonline.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nVickery recovered from a neck injury in April 1999 and played in that year\u2019s [[1999 Rugby World Cup|Rugby World Cup]]. A shoulder injury, however, kept him out of the 2000 South Africa tour. Vickery toured Australia with the [[British and Irish Lions]] in 2001 and played in all three tests.\n\nVickery was appointed captain of the England squad that toured [[Argentina]] in 2002. With many of the top players rested, Vickery led the side to victory against [[Argentina national rugby union team|The Pumas]] in [[Buenos Aires]].\n\nVickery missed the [[2003 Six Nations Championship|2003 Six Nations]] tournament because of a back injury, but having returned to the team he did well for England on the road to the [[2003 Rugby World Cup|2003 World Cup]]. He played in all seven games in the tournament, which was won by England, and captained the side against Uruguay. He scored his first international try when he came off the bench against Samoa in England\u2019s third game of the tournament.\n\nA rib injury prevented him from captaining the non capped match against the [[New Zealand Barbarians]] in December 2003. Although he took a full part in the [[2004 Six Nations Championship|2004 Six Nations]], another back operation in May ruled him out of the summer tour to New Zealand and Australia. He returned to rugby only in late October 2004.\n\nMaking his international comeback, he came on as a replacement against South Africa for the first Autumn Test between the two sides on 18 November 2006.  After playing well, he drove over to score the winning try, which was converted by [[Andy Goode]], and England won their first game since February that year.\n\nHe was selected on 2 January by new England Head Coach [[Brian Ashton (rugby player)|Brian Ashton]] to captain the side during the [[2007 Six Nations]] and [[2007 Rugby World Cup]]. He was one of only four players to have started both the 2003 and 2007 RWC Finals, the other three being [[Jonny Wilkinson]], [[Jason Robinson (rugby player)|Jason Robinson]] and [[Ben Kay]].\n\nAlso, on 8 January 2008 he was selected in the squad for the [[2008 Six Nations Championship]] by Brian Ashton. He played every game except for the 23\u201319 win over Italy which he missed through injury. He was selected to tour South Africa with the 2009 British and Irish Lions, starting the first and third test. He took a merciless pounding from Tendai Mtawarira in the first test in particular, probably the worst of his career. To his credit, he performed admirably in the third test when he replaced the injured Adam Jones to start.\n\n==Personal life==\nVickery is married to Kate and they have two children.\n\nHe was a co-commentator for [[ITV Network|ITV]]'s coverage of the [[2011 Rugby World Cup]].\n\nVickery won the 2011 series of [[Celebrity Masterchef]] beating [[Kirsty Wark]] and [[Nick Pickard]] in the final.<ref>{{cite web|title=Celebrity MasterChef dishes up 2011 winner|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-15416954|website=BBC News|accessdate=7 May 2015|date=22 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nHe was appointed a Deputy Lieutenant of Gloucestershire in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gloucestershirelive.co.uk/dame-janet-trotter-gloucestershire-8217-s-lord/story-26308504-detail/story.html|title=Ex-Gloucester Rugby star Phil Vickery among the Deputy Lord Lieutenants named for Gloucestershire|last=Qaiser|first=Maryam|date=9 April 2015|work=Gloucestershire Live|accessdate=16 December 2016}}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Cornwall}}\n*[http://www.htalentmanagement.com/client/phil-vickery Phil Vickery MBE DL Booking Agency]\n*[http://www.ragingbull.co.uk Vickery's range of clothing]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110928205852/http://www.wasps.co.uk/playerdisplaySS.ink?skip=26&season=07%2F08&seasonl=2007%2F2008&playertype=P Wasps profile]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070822060937/http://www.england-rugby.com/englandrugby/index.cfm?fuseaction=News.News_Detail&storyid=4195 England profile]\n* [http://www.lcrfc.co.uk/ London Cornish RFC]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-sports}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Neil Back]]<br>[[Martin Johnson (rugby union)|Martin Johnson]]<br>[[Martin Corry (rugby union)|Martin Corry]]<br>[[Jonny Wilkinson]]<br>[[Mike Catt]]<br>[[Martin Corry (rugby union)|Martin Corry]]<br>[[Steve Borthwick]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=English National Rugby Union Captain|years=Jun 2002<br>Nov 2003<br>Feb 2007<br>Aug 2007<br>Aug\u2013Sep 2007<br>Oct 2007 \u2013 Feb 2008<br>Feb\u2013Mar 2008}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Martin Johnson (rugby union)|Martin Johnson]]<br>[[Martin Johnson (rugby union)|Martin Johnson]]<br>[[Mike Catt]]<br>[[Mike Catt]]<br>[[Martin Corry (rugby union)|Martin Corry]]<br>[[Steve Borthwick]]<br>[[Steve Borthwick]]}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{British and Irish Lions 2009}}\n{{England Squad 2007 World Cup}}\n{{England Squad 2003 World Cup}}\n{{British and Irish Lions 2001}}\n{{England Squad 1999 World Cup}}\n{{English national rugby union team captains}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vickery, Phil}}\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Barnstaple]]\n[[Category:English rugby union players]]\n[[Category:England international rugby union players]]\n[[Category:Gloucester Rugby players]]\n[[Category:Wasps RFC players]]\n[[Category:Rugby union props]]\n[[Category:Cornish sportspeople]]\n[[Category:Cornish rugby union players]]\n[[Category:British and Irish Lions rugby union players from England]]\n[[Category:Deputy Lieutenants of Gloucestershire]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Reality cooking competition winners]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Gloucestershire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other people|Phil Vickery}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2012}}\n{{more footnotes|date=February 2009}}\n{{Infobox rugby biography \n| name = Phil Vickery\n| image = Phil Vickery.JPG\n| birth_name = Philip John Vickery\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1976|3|14|df=yes}}<ref>{{cite news |title=Phil Vickery, the Raging Bull ready to rumble |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1566688/Phil-Vickery-the-Raging-Bull-ready-to-rumble.html |accessdate=7 March 2020 |date=18 October 2007}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Barnstaple]], [[Devon]], [[England]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| height = 6 ft 3 in (1.90 m)\n| weight = 19 st 10 lb (125 kg, 275 lb)\n| girlfriend = \n| ru_position = [[Prop (rugby union)|Prop]]\n| ru_amateuryears = \n| ru_amateurclubs = \n| ru_amupdate =\n| ru_nationalteam = [[England national rugby union team|England]] <br />[[British and Irish Lions]]\n| ru_nationalyears = 1998\u20132010<br />[[2001 British and Irish Lions tour to Australia|2001]], [[2009 British and Irish Lions tour to South Africa|2009]]\n| ru_nationalcaps = 73<br />5\n| ru_nationalpoints = (10)<br />(0)\n| ru_ntupdate = 14 July 2009\n| ru_clubyears = 1995\u20132006<br />2006\u20132010\n| ru_proclubs = {{nobreak|[[Gloucester Rugby]]<br />[[Wasps RFC|London Wasps]]}}\n| ru_clubcaps = 145 <br /> 54\n| ru_clubpoints = (20) <br /> (5)\n| ru_clubupdate = 14 Dec 2010\n| ru_currentclub =\n| ru_province =\n| ru_provinceyears =\n| ru_provincecaps =\n| ru_provincepoints =\n| ru_provinceupdate =\n| ru_sevensnationalyears = \n| ru_sevensnationalteam = \n| ru_sevensnationalcaps =\n| ru_sevensnationalpoints =\n| ru_sevensupdate = \n| ru_coachclubs =\n| ru_coachyears =\n| ru_coachupdate =\n| other = \n| occupation = \n| family = \n| spouse = \n| children = \n| relatives = \n| school = \n| university = \n}}\n\n'''Philip John Vickery''' [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]] [[Deputy Lieutenant|DL]] (born 14 March 1976) is a former English rugby union [[Prop (rugby union)|tighthead prop]] and member of the [[England national rugby union team|England squad]].  He was a member of England's [[2003 Rugby Union World Cup|World Cup]] winning squad in 2003, playing in all seven matches in the tournament, and is a former England captain.  Vickery ended his club rugby career at [[Wasps RFC|London Wasps]], joining the London side in 2006 after eleven years with [[Gloucester Rugby]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guinnesspremiership.com/news/1712.php|title=News - Official Aviva Premiership Website : Post match reaction Saracens v Harlequins|work=guinnesspremiership.com}}{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>  Given the nickname \"Raging Bull\", he played in three Rugby World Cups, including as England captain in the [[2007 Rugby Union World Cup|2007 tournament]], and toured Australia and South Africa with the [[British and Irish Lions]].\n\n==Early years==\nThe son of a dairy farmer, Vickery was born to [[Cornish people|Cornish]] parents in [[Barnstaple]], [[Devon]], England and says he is proud to be a Cornishman and an [[English people|Englishman]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Phil Vickery: The long journey from farm boy to world champion |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/rugby/rugby-union/phil-vickery-the-long-journey-from-farm-boy-to-world-champion-76362.html |accessdate=7 March 2020 |work=The Independent |date=31 January 2004 |language=en}}</ref> Educated at Budehaven School, his interest in sport developed as a youngster, and by age 12 he started playing rugby.  By the age of 16 he gained his first National Representative honour, being picked for the England Schools U16s group.\n\nVickery left school age 16 and worked as a herdsman on his parents' farm.  He remains a qualified cattle inseminator.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2009/mar/14/england-france-phil-vickery-six-nations-preview|title=Rugby union: Interview: Phil Vickery tells Robert Kitson why he is still hungry for England success|author=Robert Kitson|work=the Guardian}}</ref>\n\nVickery has an Oriental [[tattoo]] on his left shoulder which roughly translates to \"''I'll fight you to the death''\", and a bulldog tattoo on his right.\n\n==Career==\nHe started with the Cornish club [[Bude RFC|Bude]], then moved to [[Redruth RFC|Redruth]], during which time he first appeared in an England Colts side.<ref>[http://www.rfu.com/2007/follow-england/profiles/phil-vickery.html  RFU profile] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081003011613/http://www.rfu.com/2007/follow-england/profiles/phil-vickery.html |date=3 October 2008 }}</ref> In 1995, England 'A' coach Richard Hill persuaded the 19-year-old Vickery to join [[Gloucester R.F.C.|Gloucester Rugby]], where he became known as \"The Raging Bull\". Whilst at Gloucester he started in the [[2001\u201302 English Premiership (rugby union)|2002 Zurich Championship Final]] (the year before winning the play-offs constituted winning the English title) in which Gloucester defeated [[Bristol Rugby]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/english/2033061.stm|title=Clockwatch: Bristol v Gloucester |publisher=BBC|date=8 June 2002 |accessdate=8 February 2018}}</ref> The following year he missed their [[2002\u201303 Powergen Cup|2003 Powergen Cup Final]] triumph through injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2003/apr/07/rugbyunion.gloucesterrugby|title=Gloucester given hope by cup win amid financial ruins |publisher=The Guardian|date=7 April 2003|accessdate=8 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/international/2797893.stm|title=Vickery out for season |publisher=BBC |date=25 February 2003|accessdate=9 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nHis representative career went from strength to strength, with appearances for England U21s and Colts in the 1996\u201397 season.\n\nIn April 2006 he announced he was quitting [[Gloucester R.F.C.|Gloucester Rugby]] after 11 years<ref>{{cite web|title=Vickery heads for Gloucester exit|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/rugby_union/english/4921714.stm|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=7 May 2015|date=21 April 2006}}</ref> and signed for [[Wasps RFC|Wasps]] in a 3-year deal.<ref>{{cite web|title=Prop Vickery seals move to Wasps|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/rugby_union/english/4942682.stm|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=7 May 2015|date=26 April 2006}}</ref> Vickery made his [[Wasps RFC|Wasps]] debut in their 23 \u2013 13 win over [[London Irish]] on 8 October 2006. With Wasps he won both the [[Heineken Cup]] in 2007<ref name=\"Heineken Cup final: Leicester 9-25 Wasps\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/6663245.stm|title=Heineken Cup final: Leicester 9\u201325 Wasps|publisher=BBC|date=19 May 2007|accessdate=6 February 2020}}</ref> and the 2008 [[Guinness Premiership]] title.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/7426519.stm |title=Guinness Premiership final |publisher=BBC|date=31 May 2008 |accessdate=6 February 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn 28 October 2010, Vickery was forced to retire from rugby after suffering from several neck injuries.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rees|first1=Paul|title=Phil Vickery calls time on playing career|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2010/oct/28/phil-vickery-to-retire|website=The Guardian|publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited|accessdate=7 May 2015|date=28 October 2010}}</ref> He played his last game at Kingsholm against Gloucester on 25 September, which is where he started his career.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/rugbyunion/international/england/8094577/England-manager-Martin-Johnson-pays-tribute-to-Phil-Vickery.html|title=England manager Martin Johnson pays tribute to Phil Vickery |date=28 October 2010|work=Telegraph|accessdate=2010-10-28}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 May 2012 Worcester Warriors announced that Vickery would join the Club as their new Assistant Forwards (Scrum) coach for the\nforthcoming 2012-2013 season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Phil Vickery joining Premiership club Worcester as a forwards coach|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2012/may/28/phil-vickery-joining-worcester|website=The Guardian|publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited|accessdate=7 May 2015|date=29 May 2012}}</ref> After an unsuccessful season, Worcester made wholesale changes in the coaching staff, from head coach through the assistants, and Vickery was one of the casualties.<ref>{{cite web|title=Worcester Warriors and Nigel Redman part company|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/rugby-union/22487723|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=7 May 2015|date=10 May 2013|quote=World Cup-winning prop Phil Vickery, brought in last summer in a consultancy role, has also left Sixways}}</ref>\n\n==Representative career==\nVickery made his England debut against Wales aged 21 on 21 February 1998, coming off the bench to replace [[Darren Garforth]] against Wales at Twickenham in the Five Nations tournament, a match England won 60\u201326.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/rugby_union/international/2784355.stm|title=BBC SPORT - Rugby Union - Internationals - Wales searching for miracles|work=bbc.co.uk}}</ref> It was the completion of a rapid rise through the England set-up, after only 34 first team games for his club and just 81 days after his England A debut.\n\n'''The Tour from Hell'''\n\nSummer 1998 saw Vickery taking part in the [[1998 England rugby union tour of Australasia and South Africa|tour of the Southern Hemisphere]], part of an England squad which had been severely weakened by injury and player unavailability.  In the space of a month, England were soundly defeated by [[Australia national rugby union team|Australia]] (76\u20130 in Brisbane on 6 June), twice by [[New Zealand national rugby union team|New Zealand]] (64\u201322 in Dunedin on 20 June and 40\u201310 in Auckland on 27 June) and finally by [[South Africa national rugby union team|South Africa]] (18\u20130 in Cape Town on 4 July).  There were also losses to New Zealand 'A', New Zealand Rugby Academy, and [[New Zealand M\u0101ori rugby union team|New Zealand M\u0101ori]].\n\nThe tour had benefits for some players, bringing through future stars of the England side such as Vickery himself, [[Jonny Wilkinson]], [[Danny Grewcock]], [[Graham Rowntree]], [[Austin Healey]], [[Matt Dawson]] and [[Matt Perry (rugby union)|Matt Perry]], others effectively had their international careers ended.  [[Steve Ravenscroft]], Rob Fidler, [[Jos Baxendell]], [[Spencer Brown (rugby player born 1973)|Spencer Brown]] and [[Tom Beim]] each gained two caps on the tour \u2013 and have not played for England since.  Richard Pool-Jones, Scott Benton, Dominic Chapman and [[Stuart Potter]] only played once for England, on the Tour From Hell.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/rugby_union/article825132.ece|title=Login|work=timesonline.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nVickery recovered from a neck injury in April 1999 and played in that year\u2019s [[1999 Rugby World Cup|Rugby World Cup]]. A shoulder injury, however, kept him out of the 2000 South Africa tour. Vickery toured Australia with the [[British and Irish Lions]] in 2001 and played in all three tests.\n\nVickery was appointed captain of the England squad that toured [[Argentina]] in 2002. With many of the top players rested, Vickery led the side to victory against [[Argentina national rugby union team|The Pumas]] in [[Buenos Aires]].\n\nVickery missed the [[2003 Six Nations Championship|2003 Six Nations]] tournament because of a back injury, but having returned to the team he did well for England on the road to the [[2003 Rugby World Cup|2003 World Cup]]. He played in all seven games in the tournament, which was won by England, and captained the side against Uruguay. He scored his first international try when he came off the bench against Samoa in England\u2019s third game of the tournament.\n\nA rib injury prevented him from captaining the non capped match against the [[New Zealand Barbarians]] in December 2003. Although he took a full part in the [[2004 Six Nations Championship|2004 Six Nations]], another back operation in May ruled him out of the summer tour to New Zealand and Australia. He returned to rugby only in late October 2004.\n\nMaking his international comeback, he came on as a replacement against South Africa for the first Autumn Test between the two sides on 18 November 2006.  After playing well, he drove over to score the winning try, which was converted by [[Andy Goode]], and England won their first game since February that year.\n\nHe was selected on 2 January by new England Head Coach [[Brian Ashton (rugby player)|Brian Ashton]] to captain the side during the [[2007 Six Nations]] and [[2007 Rugby World Cup]]. He was one of only four players to have started both the 2003 and 2007 RWC Finals, the other three being [[Jonny Wilkinson]], [[Jason Robinson (rugby player)|Jason Robinson]] and [[Ben Kay]].\n\nAlso, on 8 January 2008 he was selected in the squad for the [[2008 Six Nations Championship]] by Brian Ashton. He played every game except for the 23\u201319 win over Italy which he missed through injury. He was selected to tour South Africa with the 2009 British and Irish Lions, starting the first and third test. He took a merciless pounding from Tendai Mtawarira in the first test in particular, probably the worst of his career. To his credit, he performed admirably in the third test when he replaced the injured Adam Jones to start.\n\n==Personal life==\nVickery is married to Kate and they have two children.\n\nHe was a co-commentator for [[ITV Network|ITV]]'s coverage of the [[2011 Rugby World Cup]].\n\nVickery won the 2011 series of [[Celebrity Masterchef]] beating [[Kirsty Wark]] and [[Nick Pickard]] in the final.<ref>{{cite web|title=Celebrity MasterChef dishes up 2011 winner|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-15416954|website=BBC News|accessdate=7 May 2015|date=22 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nHe was appointed a Deputy Lieutenant of Gloucestershire in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gloucestershirelive.co.uk/dame-janet-trotter-gloucestershire-8217-s-lord/story-26308504-detail/story.html|title=Ex-Gloucester Rugby star Phil Vickery among the Deputy Lord Lieutenants named for Gloucestershire|last=Qaiser|first=Maryam|date=9 April 2015|work=Gloucestershire Live|accessdate=16 December 2016}}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.htalentmanagement.com/client/phil-vickery Phil Vickery MBE DL Booking Agency]\n*[http://www.ragingbull.co.uk Vickery's range of clothing]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110928205852/http://www.wasps.co.uk/playerdisplaySS.ink?skip=26&season=07%2F08&seasonl=2007%2F2008&playertype=P Wasps profile]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070822060937/http://www.england-rugby.com/englandrugby/index.cfm?fuseaction=News.News_Detail&storyid=4195 England profile]\n* [http://www.lcrfc.co.uk/ London Cornish RFC]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-sports}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Neil Back]]<br>[[Martin Johnson (rugby union)|Martin Johnson]]<br>[[Martin Corry (rugby union)|Martin Corry]]<br>[[Jonny Wilkinson]]<br>[[Mike Catt]]<br>[[Martin Corry (rugby union)|Martin Corry]]<br>[[Steve Borthwick]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=English National Rugby Union Captain|years=Jun 2002<br>Nov 2003<br>Feb 2007<br>Aug 2007<br>Aug\u2013Sep 2007<br>Oct 2007 \u2013 Feb 2008<br>Feb\u2013Mar 2008}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Martin Johnson (rugby union)|Martin Johnson]]<br>[[Martin Johnson (rugby union)|Martin Johnson]]<br>[[Mike Catt]]<br>[[Mike Catt]]<br>[[Martin Corry (rugby union)|Martin Corry]]<br>[[Steve Borthwick]]<br>[[Steve Borthwick]]}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{British and Irish Lions 2009}}\n{{England Squad 2007 World Cup}}\n{{England Squad 2003 World Cup}}\n{{British and Irish Lions 2001}}\n{{England Squad 1999 World Cup}}\n{{English national rugby union team captains}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vickery, Phil}}\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Barnstaple]]\n[[Category:English rugby union players]]\n[[Category:England international rugby union players]]\n[[Category:Gloucester Rugby players]]\n[[Category:Wasps RFC players]]\n[[Category:Rugby union props]]\n[[Category:Cornish sportspeople]]\n[[Category:Cornish rugby union players]]\n[[Category:British and Irish Lions rugby union players from England]]\n[[Category:Deputy Lieutenants of Gloucestershire]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Reality cooking competition winners]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Gloucestershire]]\n", "name_user": "Gazamp", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:AddedPortal:Cornwall", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phil_Vickery_(rugby_union)"}
{"title_page": "EZTV", "text_new": "{{About|the torrent distribution group|the media company|EZTV (media company)}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{original research|date=May 2015}}\n{{unreliable sources|date=May 2015}}\n}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox website\n|name            = EZTV\n|logo            = EZTV.png\n|logo_size       = 125px\n|logocaption     =\n|screenshot      =\n|collapsible     =\n|collapsetext    =\n|caption         = EZTV logo and screenshot of homepage.\n|commercial      = Yes (Advertisements)\n|type            = Torrent index, [[Magnet URI scheme|magnet links]] provider \n|registration    = \n|language        = English\n|num_users       =\n|content_license =\n|owner           =\n|author          =\n|launch_date     = <!--{{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD/no}}-->\n|revenue         =\n|footnotes       =\n|url             = }}\n\n'''EZTV''' was a TV [[Torrent file|torrent]] distribution group founded in May 2005 and dissolved in April 2015, after a hostile takeover of their domains and brand by \"EZCLOUD LIMITED\".\n\n==History==\n\n===Founding===\nIt was founded in response to the forced disappearance of TVTorrents.tv and btefnet via lawsuit.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.top10world.online |title=MPAA sues TV torrent sites |publisher=https://www.top10world.online |date= |accessdate=2012-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.top10world.online |title=Top 10 torrent websites |publisher=prasanlone |date=April 07, 2020 |accessdate=2012-03-16 }}{{|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The group was founded by a loose coalition of volunteers and holds no formal ties to its predecessors.\n\nIn the aftermath of the takedown of TVTorrents and btefnet, the [[BitTorrent]] community felt a need for a site that moderated its content. The two groups were known to never provide any fake links, a problem that used to be quite prevalent on public bittorrent sites prior to improvements in community-powered filtering in recent years. A group of volunteers gathered in the [[Internet Relay Chat|IRC]] channel #EZTV on the [[EFnet]] IRC network to create a TV torrent group from scratch in order to fill this void in the public bittorrent scene.\n\nThe idea behind EZTV was to create a group that would pick up where its two predecessors left off while avoiding what they considered the \"weak spots\" that had brought them down. This meant that EZTV should never host its own torrent files, its leadership structure should be dynamic and opaque to avoid presenting any obvious target for litigation, and the group should not host or run its own [[BitTorrent tracker|tracker]].\n\nIn addition, it was decided that EZTV should be a purely non-profit group by never asking for money of any kind from its users and to never have advertisements to avoid \"profiting from piracy\" litigation. This means that EZTV is run entirely on a volunteer basis. This clean, no-ads profile of EZTV has made the site a popular destination for the public torrent scene.\n\n===EZTVEFNET.org===\n\nDuring its first years of operation, EZTV hosted its site under the domain name eztvefnet.org. However, in October 2007 that domain began redirecting to a [[Google]] query for \"eztv\". Citing \"administrative issues\", EZTV had lost control over that domain and has redirected users to eztv.it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://torrentfreak.com/eztv-now-accessible-under-new-domain-names-071028/ |title=EZTV Now Accessible Under New Domain Names |publisher=TorrentFreak |date=October 28, 2007 |accessdate=2012-03-16}}</ref> After the Italian authorities took down the EZTV.it domain, users were directed towards eztv.ch, until the eventual demise.\n\nIn April 2008 the old domain name was [[domain parking|parked]] and taken over by a different site.\n\n===Stability issues===\n\nBy many accounts, EZTV was for a few years plagued with several periods of \u2013 sometimes prolonged \u2013 [[downtime]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://torrentfreak.com/eztv-goes-down-again-110421/ |title=EZTV Goes Down Again |publisher=TorrentFreak |date=April 21, 2011 |accessdate=2012-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.currentlydown.com/eztv.it#chart-2014-07-05\n|title=EZTV down for 14 hours\n|accessdate=2014-07-14\n}}</ref>\n\n=== Pirate Bay Raid ===\n\nOn 9 December 2014, [[The Pirate Bay]] was raided by the [[Swedish police]], who seized servers, computers, and other equipment and resulted in EZTV going down.<ref name=\"WRD-20141209\">{{cite news |last=Zetter |first=Kim |title=Pirate Bay Has Been Raided and Taken Down: Here\u2019s What We Know |url=https://www.wired.com/2014/12/pirate-bay-raided-taken-down/ |date=9 December 2014 |work=[[Wired (website)|Wired]] |accessdate=9 December 2014 }}</ref>\n\nBy the 11th of December, EZTV was releasing torrents again although the main site was not yet accessible with the regular domain, however the site could be reached through eztv proxy sites. As of 22 December 2014 EZTV was accessible again through the EZTV.ch domain for some weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://torrentfreak.com/eztv-back-online-pirate-bay-raid-141222/ |title=EZTV Is Back Online After Pirate Bay Raid |publisher=TorrentFreak |date=December 22, 2014 |accessdate=2012-12-22}}</ref>\n\n===Hostile takeover===\n\nSince October 2007, EZTV was using the EZTV.it domain name. But under pressure from copyright holders, the Italian .it registry lodged a complaint over some paperwork.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://torrentfreak.com/eztv-ditches-it-domain-after-italian-intervention-150115/  |title=EZTV DITCHES .IT DOMAIN AFTER ITALIAN INTERVENTION |publisher=TorrentFreak |date=January 15, 2015 |accessdate=2015-03-27}}</ref> Facing a possible confiscation of the EZTV.it domain name, they saw no other option than to switch to a new domain. The EZTV.it domain name was suspended, and a couple of months later was taken over by scammers<ref>{{cite web |url=http://torrentfreak.com/eztv-it-domain-compromised-by-scammers-150313/ |title=EZTV.IT DOMAIN COMPROMISED BY \u2018SCAMMERS\u2019 |publisher=TorrentFreak |date=March 13, 2015 |accessdate=2015-03-27}}</ref> attempting to claim EZTV as their own. But unlike the real EZTV this .it domain opens windows with advertisements.\n\nAs of 25 April 2015, the EZTV.ch and the EZTV-Proxy.net the \"semi\" accepted proxy are under control of \"EZCLOUD LIMITED\".<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://torrentfreak.com/take-over-new-eztv-domain-name-150425/ |title=EZTV Domain Name Falls Into New Hands |publisher=TorrentFreak |date=2015-04-25 |accessdate=2015-08-13}}</ref> Simultaneously with the takeover of the EZTV.ch domain and the EZTV-Proxy.net proxy, the scam group \"EZCLOUD LIMITED\" started attempts to take over the online identities by impersonating them on their own clone of the original websites, further assimilating the brand name and disrupting the workings and communication of the original group and attempting to gain revenue via an unofficial EZTV [[Bitcoin]] and adverts on these hijacked sites. \"EZCLOUD LIMITED\" gained access to the EZTV.se domain via the registrar and reset Novaking's information allowing them access to the domain accounts for EZTV, using this access they hijacked the EZTV domains and locked Novaking out.<ref name=\"TorrentFreak\">{{cite web |url=http://torrentfreak.com/eztv-shuts-down-after-hostile-takeover-150518/ |title=EZTV Shuts Down After Hostile Takeover |publisher=TorrentFreak |date=May 18, 2015 |accessdate=2015-05-18}}</ref>\n\nThe original EZTV website was officially retired around on 29 April 2015 with the topic of the IRC channel where EZTV was discussed saying: \"DO NOT USE THE SITES! They are not ours anymore. Thanks for all the fish.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://chat.efnet.org:9090/?channels=%23eztv&Login=Login |title=EFNET official #EZTV IRC channel |publisher=EFNET/EZTV |date=April 29, 2015 |accessdate=2015-04-29}}</ref> As of 5 May 2015 [[Rarbg]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rarbg.to/index8.php |title=Front page snapshot on web archive of RARBG mainpage - Archived April 30, 2015 |publisher=Rarbg |date=April 30, 2015 |accessdate=2015-05-07 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150430132950/https://rarbg.to/index8.php |archive-date=April 30, 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://rarbg.to/index8.php |title=RARBG Homepage |publisher=RARBG |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150430132950/https://rarbg.to/index8.php |archive-date=April 30, 2015 |df=mdy }}</ref> BT-Chat,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bt-chat.com/ |title=Front page snapshot on web archive of BT-Chat mainpage - Archived March 14, 2015 |publisher=BT-Chat |date=March 14, 2015 |accessdate=2015-05-07 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150314235503/http://www.bt-chat.com/ |archive-date=March 14, 2015 }}</ref> and other sites have removed EZTV as an affiliate and are taking steps to stop \"EZCLOUD LIMITED\" indexing releases. [[KickassTorrents]], BT-Chat and [[The Pirate Bay]] have since suspended or deactivated the official EZTV accounts and added warning to the old releases, also ex-EZTV staff continue their warnings that people should avoid the scam site that is left behind.<ref name=\"TorrentFreak\"/>\n\n==Former partners==\n\nOver the years, EZTV has participated in several partnerships.\n\n===EZTV and VTV===\n\nInitially, EZTV and fellow TV torrent distribution group VTV acted as competition across the board but with different approaches. Over time, however, it has become clear that the two groups cooperate in some ways since VTV distributes releases that EZTV does not do via EZTV's IRC channel and website.\n\n===EZTV and MVGroup===\n\nIn summer of 2008, EZTV and the documentary torrent distribution group [[MVGroup]] initiated a partnership that saw MVG's torrents distributed by EZTV on their IRC channel and website. The agreement benefited both sides, as MVG gained increased exposure and a vastly improved seeder base while EZTV expanded the list of shows available through them.\n\nIn a statement to TorrentFreak, MVGroup admins said they \"would like to take this opportunity to thank EZTV in helping us continue our founder's legacy, to spread high quality educational material via p2p, to everyone, for free (...)\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://torrentfreak.com/eztv-and-mvgroup-join-forces-080605/ |title=EZTV and MVGroup Join Forces |publisher=TorrentFreak |date=June 5, 2008 |accessdate=2012-03-16}}</ref>\n\nOne month prior to this announcement, MVG's founder Merrin had died after prolonged illness.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://torrentfreak.com/bittorrent-community-mourns-as-tracker-founder-passes-away-080513/ |title=BitTorrent Community Mourns as Tracker Founder Passes Away |publisher=TorrentFreak |date=May 13, 2008 |accessdate=2012-03-16}}</ref>\n\n===EZTV and VODO===\n\nThe Creative Commons media distributor [[VODO]] has for a long time held a prominent position on the EZTV site. EZTV was one of the first torrent groups to offer VODO exposure to their audience, along with [[The Pirate Bay]], [[Mininova]], [[isoHunt]] and others.<ref>{{cite web|last=Doctorow |first=Cory |url=http://boingboing.net/2009/10/15/vodo-a-filesharing-s.html |title=Vodo: a filesharing service for film-makers |publisher=Boing Boing |date=October 15, 2009 |accessdate=2012-03-16}}</ref>\n\n==April Fools==\n[[File:EZTV Aptil Fools 2014 \"New Design\".jpg|thumb|right|EZTV Homepage April 1, 2014|alt=EZTV Homepage April 1st 2014]]\nOne notable exception to the no-fakes mechanic was a 2008 [[April Fools' Day|April Fools' Day prank]], where a release was posted on EZTV's website purporting to be a DVD [[screener (promotional)|screener]] pre-air release of an episode of the TV-show ''[[Lost (TV series)|Lost]]''. This episode was, in fact, an episode of ''[[Flavor of Love]]'' with an edit at the beginning saying \"April Fool's\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tv.com/shows/lost/forums/eztvs-april-fools-joke-11431-1034773/ |title=Lost: eztv's april fool's joke |publisher=TV.com |date= |accessdate=2012-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3tejf20IN-E |title=Lost 4x09? No. It's April Fool's |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=2012-03-16}}</ref>\n\nA year after the Lost pre-air incident, the group replaced their site with a service dedicated to sports related shows \u2013 EZSports.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neowin.net/forum/topic/753884-ezsports/ |title=EZSPORTS \u2013 Neowin Forums |publisher=Neowin.net |date=April 1, 2009 |accessdate=2012-03-16}}</ref> In the aftermath of this prank, many users actually wanted the group to let the EZSports site stay online and be provided as a parallel service to the regular EZTV. The group was initially positive to the idea, but a lack of volunteers to maintain the site stopped it in its tracks.\n\nIn 2012 the group pulled another April Fools' Day prank on the community. This time they renamed their releases with the extension .rm ([[RealMedia]]) and posted an announcement on the site explaining they had changed the format of their releases in response to \"all the comments people have been leaving on our forums\" after [[Warez scene|the Scene]] changed the encoding of their releases in the weeks prior to the prank.<ref>{{cite web|author=EZTV.ch |url=https://eztv.ch/news/77/real-mediay-click-here/ |title=Real Media? click here! |publisher=EZTV.ch |date= |accessdate=2015-02-20}}</ref>\n\n==ISP Blockade==\nEZTV and its [[RSS]] website ezRSS are currently blocked by multiple [[Internet service provider|ISPs]] in Italy and in the UK at request from [[Motion Picture Association|MPA]] and [[Federation Against Copyright Theft|FACT]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://torrentfreak.com/movie-studios-win-isp-blockade-against-eztv-and-yify-torrents-130722/ |title=Movie Studios Win ISP Blockade Against EZTV and YIFY-Torrents |publisher=TorrentFreak |date=2013-07-22 |accessdate=2015-08-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://community.virginmedia.com/t5/Announcements/EZTV-Blocked-by-Court-Order/m-p/1923144 |accessdate=July 26, 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130731181453/http://community.virginmedia.com/t5/Announcements/EZTV-Blocked-by-Court-Order/m-p/1923144 | title= EZTV Blocked by Court Order |archive-date=July 31, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://torrentfreak.com/uk-internet-providers-start-blocking-eztv-and-ezrss-130726/ |title=UK Internet Providers Start Blocking EZTV and ezRSS |publisher=TorrentFreak |date=2013-07-26 |accessdate=2015-08-13}}</ref>\n\nAs of August 2017, Australian ISP's have also blocked EZTV, amongst others.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Comparison of BitTorrent sites]]\n* [[Standard (warez)#x264 for television sources|Standard (warez)]]\n* [[Websites blocked in the United Kingdom]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{BitTorrent}}\n\n[[Category:Defunct BitTorrent websites]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the torrent distribution group|the media company|EZTV (media company)}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{original research|date=May 2015}}\n{{unreliable sources|date=May 2015}}\n}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox website\n|name            = EZTV\n|logo            = EZTV.png\n|logo_size       = 125px\n|logocaption     =\n|screenshot      =\n|collapsible     =\n|collapsetext    =\n|caption         = EZTV logo and screenshot of homepage.\n|commercial      = Yes (Advertisements)\n|type            = Torrent index, [[Magnet URI scheme|magnet links]] provider \n|registration    = \n|language        = English\n|num_users       =\n|content_license =\n|owner           =\n|author          =\n|launch_date     = <!--{{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD/no}}-->\n|revenue         =\n|footnotes       =\n|url             = }}\n\n'''EZTV''' was a TV [[Torrent file|torrent]] distribution group founded in May 2005 and dissolved in April 2015, after a hostile takeover of their domains and brand by \"EZCLOUD LIMITED\".\n\n==History==\n\n===Founding===\nIt was founded in response to the forced disappearance of TVTorrents.tv and btefnet via lawsuit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://piracyisnotacrime.com/tvtorrent.php |title=MPAA sues TV torrent sites |publisher=Piracyisnotacrime.com |date= |accessdate=2012-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://digg.com/news/story/tvtorrents_is_down....for_good |title=tvtorrents is down for good |publisher=Digg |date=April 22, 2005 |accessdate=2012-03-16 }}{{Dead link|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The group was founded by a loose coalition of volunteers and holds no formal ties to its predecessors.\n\nIn the aftermath of the takedown of TVTorrents and btefnet, the [[BitTorrent]] community felt a need for a site that moderated its content. The two groups were known to never provide any fake links, a problem that used to be quite prevalent on public bittorrent sites prior to improvements in community-powered filtering in recent years. A group of volunteers gathered in the [[Internet Relay Chat|IRC]] channel #EZTV on the [[EFnet]] IRC network to create a TV torrent group from scratch in order to fill this void in the public bittorrent scene.\n\nThe idea behind EZTV was to create a group that would pick up where its two predecessors left off while avoiding what they considered the \"weak spots\" that had brought them down. This meant that EZTV should never host its own torrent files, its leadership structure should be dynamic and opaque to avoid presenting any obvious target for litigation, and the group should not host or run its own [[BitTorrent tracker|tracker]].\n\nIn addition, it was decided that EZTV should be a purely non-profit group by never asking for money of any kind from its users and to never have advertisements to avoid \"profiting from piracy\" litigation. This means that EZTV is run entirely on a volunteer basis. This clean, no-ads profile of EZTV has made the site a popular destination for the public torrent scene.\n\n===EZTVEFNET.org===\n\nDuring its first years of operation, EZTV hosted its site under the domain name eztvefnet.org. However, in October 2007 that domain began redirecting to a [[Google]] query for \"eztv\". Citing \"administrative issues\", EZTV had lost control over that domain and has redirected users to eztv.it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://torrentfreak.com/eztv-now-accessible-under-new-domain-names-071028/ |title=EZTV Now Accessible Under New Domain Names |publisher=TorrentFreak |date=October 28, 2007 |accessdate=2012-03-16}}</ref> After the Italian authorities took down the EZTV.it domain, users were directed towards eztv.ch, until the eventual demise.\n\nIn April 2008 the old domain name was [[domain parking|parked]] and taken over by a different site.\n\n===Stability issues===\n\nBy many accounts, EZTV was for a few years plagued with several periods of \u2013 sometimes prolonged \u2013 [[downtime]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://torrentfreak.com/eztv-goes-down-again-110421/ |title=EZTV Goes Down Again |publisher=TorrentFreak |date=April 21, 2011 |accessdate=2012-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.currentlydown.com/eztv.it#chart-2014-07-05\n|title=EZTV down for 14 hours\n|accessdate=2014-07-14\n}}</ref>\n\n=== Pirate Bay Raid ===\n\nOn 9 December 2014, [[The Pirate Bay]] was raided by the [[Swedish police]], who seized servers, computers, and other equipment and resulted in EZTV going down.<ref name=\"WRD-20141209\">{{cite news |last=Zetter |first=Kim |title=Pirate Bay Has Been Raided and Taken Down: Here\u2019s What We Know |url=https://www.wired.com/2014/12/pirate-bay-raided-taken-down/ |date=9 December 2014 |work=[[Wired (website)|Wired]] |accessdate=9 December 2014 }}</ref>\n\nBy the 11th of December, EZTV was releasing torrents again although the main site was not yet accessible with the regular domain, however the site could be reached through eztv proxy sites. As of 22 December 2014 EZTV was accessible again through the EZTV.ch domain for some weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://torrentfreak.com/eztv-back-online-pirate-bay-raid-141222/ |title=EZTV Is Back Online After Pirate Bay Raid |publisher=TorrentFreak |date=December 22, 2014 |accessdate=2012-12-22}}</ref>\n\n===Hostile takeover===\n\nSince October 2007, EZTV was using the EZTV.it domain name. But under pressure from copyright holders, the Italian .it registry lodged a complaint over some paperwork.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://torrentfreak.com/eztv-ditches-it-domain-after-italian-intervention-150115/  |title=EZTV DITCHES .IT DOMAIN AFTER ITALIAN INTERVENTION |publisher=TorrentFreak |date=January 15, 2015 |accessdate=2015-03-27}}</ref> Facing a possible confiscation of the EZTV.it domain name, they saw no other option than to switch to a new domain. The EZTV.it domain name was suspended, and a couple of months later was taken over by scammers<ref>{{cite web |url=http://torrentfreak.com/eztv-it-domain-compromised-by-scammers-150313/ |title=EZTV.IT DOMAIN COMPROMISED BY \u2018SCAMMERS\u2019 |publisher=TorrentFreak |date=March 13, 2015 |accessdate=2015-03-27}}</ref> attempting to claim EZTV as their own. But unlike the real EZTV this .it domain opens windows with advertisements.\n\nAs of 25 April 2015, the EZTV.ch and the EZTV-Proxy.net the \"semi\" accepted proxy are under control of \"EZCLOUD LIMITED\".<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://torrentfreak.com/take-over-new-eztv-domain-name-150425/ |title=EZTV Domain Name Falls Into New Hands |publisher=TorrentFreak |date=2015-04-25 |accessdate=2015-08-13}}</ref> Simultaneously with the takeover of the EZTV.ch domain and the EZTV-Proxy.net proxy, the scam group \"EZCLOUD LIMITED\" started attempts to take over the online identities by impersonating them on their own clone of the original websites, further assimilating the brand name and disrupting the workings and communication of the original group and attempting to gain revenue via an unofficial EZTV [[Bitcoin]] and adverts on these hijacked sites. \"EZCLOUD LIMITED\" gained access to the EZTV.se domain via the registrar and reset Novaking's information allowing them access to the domain accounts for EZTV, using this access they hijacked the EZTV domains and locked Novaking out.<ref name=\"TorrentFreak\">{{cite web |url=http://torrentfreak.com/eztv-shuts-down-after-hostile-takeover-150518/ |title=EZTV Shuts Down After Hostile Takeover |publisher=TorrentFreak |date=May 18, 2015 |accessdate=2015-05-18}}</ref>\n\nThe original EZTV website was officially retired around on 29 April 2015 with the topic of the IRC channel where EZTV was discussed saying: \"DO NOT USE THE SITES! They are not ours anymore. Thanks for all the fish.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://chat.efnet.org:9090/?channels=%23eztv&Login=Login |title=EFNET official #EZTV IRC channel |publisher=EFNET/EZTV |date=April 29, 2015 |accessdate=2015-04-29}}</ref> As of 5 May 2015 [[Rarbg]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rarbg.to/index8.php |title=Front page snapshot on web archive of RARBG mainpage - Archived April 30, 2015 |publisher=Rarbg |date=April 30, 2015 |accessdate=2015-05-07 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150430132950/https://rarbg.to/index8.php |archive-date=April 30, 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://rarbg.to/index8.php |title=RARBG Homepage |publisher=RARBG |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150430132950/https://rarbg.to/index8.php |archive-date=April 30, 2015 |df=mdy }}</ref> BT-Chat,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bt-chat.com/ |title=Front page snapshot on web archive of BT-Chat mainpage - Archived March 14, 2015 |publisher=BT-Chat |date=March 14, 2015 |accessdate=2015-05-07 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150314235503/http://www.bt-chat.com/ |archive-date=March 14, 2015 }}</ref> and other sites have removed EZTV as an affiliate and are taking steps to stop \"EZCLOUD LIMITED\" indexing releases. [[KickassTorrents]], BT-Chat and [[The Pirate Bay]] have since suspended or deactivated the official EZTV accounts and added warning to the old releases, also ex-EZTV staff continue their warnings that people should avoid the scam site that is left behind.<ref name=\"TorrentFreak\"/>\n\n==Former partners==\n\nOver the years, EZTV has participated in several partnerships.\n\n===EZTV and VTV===\n\nInitially, EZTV and fellow TV torrent distribution group VTV acted as competition across the board but with different approaches. Over time, however, it has become clear that the two groups cooperate in some ways since VTV distributes releases that EZTV does not do via EZTV's IRC channel and website.\n\n===EZTV and MVGroup===\n\nIn summer of 2008, EZTV and the documentary torrent distribution group [[MVGroup]] initiated a partnership that saw MVG's torrents distributed by EZTV on their IRC channel and website. The agreement benefited both sides, as MVG gained increased exposure and a vastly improved seeder base while EZTV expanded the list of shows available through them.\n\nIn a statement to TorrentFreak, MVGroup admins said they \"would like to take this opportunity to thank EZTV in helping us continue our founder's legacy, to spread high quality educational material via p2p, to everyone, for free (...)\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://torrentfreak.com/eztv-and-mvgroup-join-forces-080605/ |title=EZTV and MVGroup Join Forces |publisher=TorrentFreak |date=June 5, 2008 |accessdate=2012-03-16}}</ref>\n\nOne month prior to this announcement, MVG's founder Merrin had died after prolonged illness.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://torrentfreak.com/bittorrent-community-mourns-as-tracker-founder-passes-away-080513/ |title=BitTorrent Community Mourns as Tracker Founder Passes Away |publisher=TorrentFreak |date=May 13, 2008 |accessdate=2012-03-16}}</ref>\n\n===EZTV and VODO===\n\nThe Creative Commons media distributor [[VODO]] has for a long time held a prominent position on the EZTV site. EZTV was one of the first torrent groups to offer VODO exposure to their audience, along with [[The Pirate Bay]], [[Mininova]], [[isoHunt]] and others.<ref>{{cite web|last=Doctorow |first=Cory |url=http://boingboing.net/2009/10/15/vodo-a-filesharing-s.html |title=Vodo: a filesharing service for film-makers |publisher=Boing Boing |date=October 15, 2009 |accessdate=2012-03-16}}</ref>\n\n==April Fools==\n[[File:EZTV Aptil Fools 2014 \"New Design\".jpg|thumb|right|EZTV Homepage April 1, 2014|alt=EZTV Homepage April 1st 2014]]\nOne notable exception to the no-fakes mechanic was a 2008 [[April Fools' Day|April Fools' Day prank]], where a release was posted on EZTV's website purporting to be a DVD [[screener (promotional)|screener]] pre-air release of an episode of the TV-show ''[[Lost (TV series)|Lost]]''. This episode was, in fact, an episode of ''[[Flavor of Love]]'' with an edit at the beginning saying \"April Fool's\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tv.com/shows/lost/forums/eztvs-april-fools-joke-11431-1034773/ |title=Lost: eztv's april fool's joke |publisher=TV.com |date= |accessdate=2012-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3tejf20IN-E |title=Lost 4x09? No. It's April Fool's |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=2012-03-16}}</ref>\n\nA year after the Lost pre-air incident, the group replaced their site with a service dedicated to sports related shows \u2013 EZSports.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neowin.net/forum/topic/753884-ezsports/ |title=EZSPORTS \u2013 Neowin Forums |publisher=Neowin.net |date=April 1, 2009 |accessdate=2012-03-16}}</ref> In the aftermath of this prank, many users actually wanted the group to let the EZSports site stay online and be provided as a parallel service to the regular EZTV. The group was initially positive to the idea, but a lack of volunteers to maintain the site stopped it in its tracks.\n\nIn 2012 the group pulled another April Fools' Day prank on the community. This time they renamed their releases with the extension .rm ([[RealMedia]]) and posted an announcement on the site explaining they had changed the format of their releases in response to \"all the comments people have been leaving on our forums\" after [[Warez scene|the Scene]] changed the encoding of their releases in the weeks prior to the prank.<ref>{{cite web|author=EZTV.ch |url=https://eztv.ch/news/77/real-mediay-click-here/ |title=Real Media? click here! |publisher=EZTV.ch |date= |accessdate=2015-02-20}}</ref>\n\n==ISP Blockade==\nEZTV and its [[RSS]] website ezRSS are currently blocked by multiple [[Internet service provider|ISPs]] in Italy and in the UK at request from [[Motion Picture Association|MPA]] and [[Federation Against Copyright Theft|FACT]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://torrentfreak.com/movie-studios-win-isp-blockade-against-eztv-and-yify-torrents-130722/ |title=Movie Studios Win ISP Blockade Against EZTV and YIFY-Torrents |publisher=TorrentFreak |date=2013-07-22 |accessdate=2015-08-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://community.virginmedia.com/t5/Announcements/EZTV-Blocked-by-Court-Order/m-p/1923144 |accessdate=July 26, 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130731181453/http://community.virginmedia.com/t5/Announcements/EZTV-Blocked-by-Court-Order/m-p/1923144 | title= EZTV Blocked by Court Order |archive-date=July 31, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://torrentfreak.com/uk-internet-providers-start-blocking-eztv-and-ezrss-130726/ |title=UK Internet Providers Start Blocking EZTV and ezRSS |publisher=TorrentFreak |date=2013-07-26 |accessdate=2015-08-13}}</ref>\n\nAs of August 2017, Australian ISP's have also blocked EZTV, amongst others.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Comparison of BitTorrent sites]]\n* [[Standard (warez)#x264 for television sources|Standard (warez)]]\n* [[Websites blocked in the United Kingdom]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{BitTorrent}}\n\n[[Category:Defunct BitTorrent websites]]\n", "name_user": "PrasanLone", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/EZTV"}
