{"title_page": "They're Coming to Take Me Away, Ha-Haaa!", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = They're Coming to Take Me Away, Ha-Haaa!\n| cover      = TheyreComingToTakeMeAway-singlecover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = Cover of the Rhino Records co. re-issue of the WB album\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Napoleon XIV]]\n| album      =\n| B-side     = !aaaH-aH ,yawA eM ekaT oT gnimoC er'yehT\n| released   = July 1966\n| format     = [[Gramophone record|7-inch single]]\n| recorded   = 1966\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Novelty song|Novelty]], [[Comedy music|comedy]]\n| length     = 2:10\n| label      = [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]] #5831\n| writer     = N. Bonaparte ([[Jerry Samuels]])\n| producer   = A Jepalana Production\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = I'm in Love with My Little Red Tricycle\n| next_year  = 1966\n| misc       = {{Extra album cover\n | header  = B-side\n | type    = single\n | cover   = Napoleon Xiv B side Original Issue.jpg\n | border  =\n | alt     =\n | caption = Label of the original 7-inch issue\n}}\n}}\n\n'''They're Coming to Take Me Away, Ha-Haaa!''' is a 1966 [[Novelty song|novelty]] record written and performed by Jerry Samuels (billed as [[Napoleon XIV]]), and released on [[Warner Bros. Records]]. The song became an instant success in the United States, peaking at No. 3 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] popular music singles chart on August 13<ref>[[Joel Whitburn]], ''The Billboard Book of Top 40 Hits'', Billboard Publications, 1983.</ref>, No. 1 on the [[Cash Box Top 100]] charts, No. 2 in Canada, and reaching No. 4 on the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref>''Joel Whitburn's Top Pop Singles 1955-1990'' - {{ISBN|0-89820-089-X}}</ref>\n\n== Lyrics ==\nThe lyrics appear to describe a man's mental anguish after a break-up with a woman, and his descent into madness leading to his committal to a \"funny farm\" (slang for a [[psychiatric hospital|mental hospital]]). It\u2019s finally revealed in last line of the third verse that he\u2019s not being driven insane by the loss of a woman \u2014 but by a runaway dog: \"They'll find you yet and when they do, they'll put you in the [[American Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals|ASPCA]], you mangy mutt\". According to Samuels, he was concerned the record could be seen as making fun of the mentally ill, and intentionally added that line so \"you realize that the person is talking about a dog having left him, not a human\". Said Samuels, \"I felt it would cause some people to say 'Well, it's alright.' And it did. It worked.\"<ref name=\"Crouse2000\">{{cite book|author=Richard Crouse|title=Big Bang, Baby: Rock Trivia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dYFv3ifE0f4C&pg=PA91|date=26 April 2000|publisher=Dundurn|isbn=978-0-88882-219-2|pages=91\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Crouse2012\">{{cite book|author=Richard Crouse|title=Who Wrote The Book Of Love?|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OyZyWKcmRhEC&pg=PT70|date=15 March 2012|publisher=Doubleday Canada|isbn=978-0-385-67442-3|pages=70\u2013}}</ref>\n\n== Song structure ==\nThe song is driven by a [[snare drum]], [[tambourine]] and hand clap rhythm. The vocal is spoken rhythmically rather than sung melodically, while the vocal pitch rises and falls at key points to create an unusual [[glissando]] effect, augmented by the sound of wailing sirens.<ref name=\"Crouse2012\" /><ref name=\"SF1\" /> \n\n== Technical background ==\nAccording to Samuels, the vocal glissando was achieved by manipulating the recording speed of his vocal track, a multitrack variation on the technique used by [[Ross Bagdasarian, Sr.|Ross Bagdasarian]] in creating the original [[The Chipmunks|Chipmunks]] novelty songs.<ref name=\"Crouse2012\" /> At the time the song was written, Samuels was working as a recording engineer at Associated Recording Studios in New York. Samuels discovered he could use a [[Variable Frequency Oscillator]] to alter the 60\u00a0[[Hz]] [[Utility frequency|frequency]] of the [[Synchronous_motor#Hysteresis_motors|hysteresis motor]] of a [[Multitrack recording|multitrack]] tape recording machine in order to raise or lower the pitch of a voice without changing the tempo. This gave him the idea for a song based on the rhythm of the old Scottish tune \"[[The Campbells Are Coming]]\". After recording a percussion track at the standard speed, he played it back through headphones while recording the vocal on another track and gradually adjusting the VFO and the pace of his vocals to produce the desired effect. Some tracks were treated with intermittent tape-based echo effects created by an [[Echoplex]]. Samuels also layered in siren effects that gradually rose and fell with the pitch of his vocals.<ref name=\"Everett2008\">{{cite book|author=Walter Everett|title=The Foundations of Rock: From \"Blue Suede Shoes\" to \"Suite: Judy Blue Eyes\"|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P3NMCAAAQBAJ&pg=PT485|date=9 December 2008|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-029497-7|pages=485\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"SF1\">{{cite web |title=They're Coming To Take Me Away, Ha-haaa by Napoleon XIV |url=https://www.songfacts.com/facts/napoleon-xiv/theyre-coming-to-take-me-away-ha-haaa |website=SongFacts.com |publisher=SongFacts |accessdate=17 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n== B-side ==\nContinuing the theme of insanity, the flip or [[B-side]] of the single was simply the A-side [[backmasking|played in reverse]], and given the title \"!aaaH-aH ,yawA eM ekaT oT gnimoC er'yehT\" (or \"<span style=\"transform: scaleX(-1); display: inline-block;\">Ha-Haaa!</span> <span style=\"transform: scaleX(-1); display: inline-block;\">Away,</span> <span style=\"transform: scaleX(-1); display: inline-block;\">Me</span> <span style=\"transform: scaleX(-1); display: inline-block;\">Take</span> <span style=\"transform: scaleX(-1); display: inline-block;\">to</span> <span style=\"transform: scaleX(-1); display: inline-block;\">Coming</span> <span style=\"transform: scaleX(-1); display: inline-block;\">They're</span>\") and the performer billed as \"<span style=\"transform: scaleX(-1); display: inline-block;\">XIV</span> <span style=\"transform: scaleX(-1); display: inline-block;\">NAPOLEON</span>\". Most of the label affixed to the B-side was a mirror image of the front label (as opposed to simply being spelled backward), including the letters in the \"WB\" shield logo. Only the label name, disclaimer, and record and recording master numbers were kept frontward. The reverse version of the song is not included on the original Warner Bros. album, although the title is shown on the front cover, whereas the title is actually spelled backward.<ref name=\"Simpson2003\">{{cite book|author=Paul Simpson|title=The Rough Guide to Cult Pop|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=F7hpXcrqA-8C&pg=PA23|year=2003|publisher=Rough Guides|isbn=978-1-84353-229-3|pages=23\u2013}}</ref>\n\nIn his ''Book of Rock Lists'', rock music critic [[Dave Marsh]] calls the B-side the \"most obnoxious song ever to appear in a [[jukebox]]\", saying the recording once \"cleared out a [[diner]] of forty patrons in three minutes flat.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=The Book of Rock Lists|first=Dave|last=Marsh|first2=Kevin|last2=Stein|publisher=Dell Publishing|year=1981|p=[https://archive.org/details/bookofrocklists00mars/page/80 80]|isbn=978-0-440-57580-1|url=https://archive.org/details/bookofrocklists00mars/page/80}}</ref>\n\n== Airplay ==\nThe song charted at No. 3 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] charts on August 13<ref>[[Joel Whitburn]], ''The Billboard Book of Top 40 Hits'', Billboard Publications, 1983.</ref>, No. 1 on the [[Cash Box Top 100]] charts on July 30, No. 2 in Canada, and reaching No. 4 on the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref>''Joel Whitburn's Top Pop Singles 1955-1990'' - {{ISBN|0-89820-089-X}}</ref>\n\nWithin weeks of its release, [[WABC (AM)|WABC]] and [[WMCA (AM)|WMCA]] stopped playing the song in response to complaints about its content from mental health professionals and organizations.<ref name=\"SF2\">{{cite web |title=They're Coming To Take Me Away, Ha-Haaa! Napoleon XIV |url=https://www.songfacts.com/image/napoleon-xiv/theyre-coming-to-take-me-away-ha-haaa |website=Songfacts.com |publisher=Songfacts |accessdate=18 June 2019}}</ref> The [[BBC]] also refused to play the song.\n\nWarner Bros. Records reissued the original single (#7726) in 1973. It entered the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] at No. 87 but stalled at No. 101 at the Week Ahead charts which was an addition to the [[Cash Box Top 100]] charts. The reissue featured the \"Burbank/palm trees\" label.  As with the original release, the labels for the reissue's B-side also included mirror-imaged print except for the disclaimer, record catalog, and track master numbers.  The \"Burbank\" motto at the top of the label was also kept frontward as well as the \"WB\" letters in the shield logo, which had been printed in reverse on the originals.<ref name=\"Collins1998\">{{cite book|author=Ace Collins|title=Disco Duck and Other Adventures in Novelty Music|url=https://archive.org/details/discoduckotherad0000coll|url-access=registration|year=1998|publisher=Berkley Boulevard Books|isbn=978-0-425-16358-0|pages=[https://archive.org/details/discoduckotherad0000coll/page/210 210]\u2013211}}</ref>\n\n==Chart history==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1966)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])<ref>[http://www.poparchives.com.au/gosetcharts/1966/19661005.html Go-Set National Top 40, 5 October 1966]</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|40\n|-\n|Canada ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'' Top Singles<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/item.aspx?IdNumber=4323&|title=Item Display - RPM - Library and Archives Canada |website=Collectionscanada.gc.ca |date=1966-08-15 |accessdate=2018-08-16}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n|[[UK Singles Chart|UK]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/12632/napoleon-xiv/ |title=Official Charts Company |website=Officialcharts.com |date=1966-08-10 |accessdate=2018-08-16}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n|-\n|U.S. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]] <ref>''Joel Whitburn's Top Pop Singles 1955-1990'' - {{ISBN|0-89820-089-X}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n|U.S. [[Cash Box (magazine)|''Cash Box'']] Top 100<ref>[http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/60s_files/19660730.html Cash Box Top 100 Singles, July 30, 1966]</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|-\n|}\n\n==Sequels==\n\"I'm Happy They Took You Away, Ha-Haaa!\" was recorded by [[CBS Radio Mystery Theater]] cast member Bryna Raeburn, credited as \"Josephine XV\", and was the closing track on Side Two of the 1966 Warner Bros. album.  ([[Jos\u00e9phine de Beauharnais|Josephine]] was the name of the spouse of the French Emperor [[Napoleon Bonaparte]].)\n\nA variation of \"They're Coming to Take Me Away, Ha-Haaa!\" was also done by Jerry Samuels, from that same album entitled ''Where the Nuts hunt the Squirrels'', where Samuels, towards the end of the track, repeats the line: \"THEY'RE TRYING TO DRIVE ME SANE!!! HA HA,\" before the song's fade, in a fast-tracked higher voice.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.guitarcenter.com/M-Audio/Fast-Track-MKII-USB-Audio-Interface-1274115051782.gc |title=M-Audio Fast Track MKII USB Audio Interface |publisher=Guitar Center |date=2011-12-29 |accessdate=2016-09-29}}</ref>\n\nIn 1966, [[KRDC (AM)|KRLA]] [[DJ]] [[Hudson & Landry|\"Emperor Bob\" Hudson]] recorded a similarly styled song titled ''I'm Normal'', including the lines \"They came and took my brother away/The men in white picked him up yesterday/But they'll never come take me away, 'cos I'm O.K./I'm normal.\" Another line in the song was: \"I eat my peas with a tuning fork.\" The record was credited simply to \"The Emperor.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kfxm.com/EmperorHudson.htm |title=Emperor Hudson |website=Kfxm.com |date= |accessdate=2016-09-29}}</ref>\n\nIn 1988, Samuels wrote and recorded \"They're Coming To Get Me Again, Ha Haaa!\", a sequel to the original record. It was included on a single two years later on the ''Collectables'' label. Recorded with the same beat as the original, and portraying Napoleon XIV relapsing to madness after being released from an [[insane asylum]], it never charted, and was combined with the original 1966 recording on side A. (Both sequels are included on Samuels' 1996 ''Second Coming'' album.) In the song, instead of a \"mangy mutt,\" for his lost dog, Napoleon bemoans the loss of his pet monkey. (\"I'll swing you by your tail, you hairy ape!\") In the song, instead of the \"funny farm\" and the \"happy home\" Napoleon XIV is being taken away to the \"loony bin\" and the \"rubber room.\" Towards the end of the song, he relapses into the \"funny farm\" and \"happy home\"\u2014until when reality sinks in, he cries out at a fast tracked double voice with the words: \"OH NO!!!\" before the beat ends with a door slam, indicating that he has been locked up in the insane asylum.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfxsource.com/sound-effects/door-sound-effects/door-slam-sound-effects.html |title=Door Slam Sound Effects, Door Slam Sounds, Door Slam Sound Effect, Door Slam Sound Clips |website=Sfxsource.com |date= |accessdate=2016-09-29}}</ref>\n\nThe recording appeared on disk releases by [[Dr. Demento]] in 1975 as part of ''Dr. Demento's Delights'',<ref name=\"Inc.1975\">\"Billboard's Recommended LPs\". {{cite book|author=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|title=Billboard|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=exEEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA72|date=15 November 1975|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|pages=72\u2013|issn=0006-2510}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Newsweek|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uaoeAQAAMAAJ|date=October 1975|publisher=Newsweek, Incorporated|page=86}}</ref> then in subsequent Dr. Demento LP records released in 1985, 1988 and 1991.\n\n== Cover versions ==\n[[Kim Fowley]] released a cover of the song as his second single, after \"The Trip\".<ref name=\"Larkin2011\">{{cite book|author=Colin Larkin|title=The Encyclopedia of Popular Music|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_NNmFiUnSmUC&pg=PA2178|date=27 May 2011|publisher=Omnibus Press|isbn=978-0-85712-595-8|pages=2178\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Inc.1966\">\"International news reports\". {{cite book|author=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|title=Billboard|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EREEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA55|date=20 August 1966|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|pages=55\u2013|issn=0006-2510}}</ref>\n\nIn the UK a cover version was also released in November 1966 by the humorous pop group [[The Barron Knights]] where it was included on the B-side of their single \"Under New Management\".<ref>{{cite web|title=The Barron-Knights \u2013 Under New Management|url=http://www.45cat.com/record/db8071|website=45cat |accessdate=5 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[The Monkees]]' song \"Gonna Buy Me a Dog\", sung by [[Micky Dolenz]], features [[Davy Jones (actor)|Davy Jones]] teasing Dolenz toward the fade of the song with the words \"they're coming to take us away\" taken from Napoleon XIV's song.\n\nIn Argentina Pedro ''Pelusa'' Suero (a well known actor, announcer, and voice over) recorded, as \"Napole\u00f3n Puppy\", a cover in Spanish of this song titled \"Ellos me quieren llevar\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Napoleon Puppy \u2013 Discography|url=http://www.discogs.com/Napoleon-Puppy-Ellos-Me-Quieren-Llevar-Trisagio-Del-Soltero/release/6010916|website=Discogs |accessdate=17 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Jeff Duff]], as \"Cyril Trotts\", covered \"They're Coming To Take Me Away, Ha! Ha!\" in 1984 on his ''To Bogna'' LP.\n\nExperimental music band [[Nurse With Wound]] used some of the lyrics from the song for their limited 7\" release \"No Hiding from the Blackbird/Burial Of The Sardine\".\n\n[[Biz Markie]] also covers this song on ''[[Make the Music with Your Mouth, Biz]]'' in 1986, but he changes most of the lyrics.\n\n[[Austen Tayshus]] covered the song on his 1988 album ''Whispering Joke'' and also as a single. The B-side (a reversed version) was recreated as well.\n\n[[Jello Biafra]] covered this song with his band [[Lard (band)|Lard]] on their album ''[[The Last Temptation of Reid]]'' in 1990.\n\nIn 1998, [[Amanda Lear]] included this song in her compilation ''Made in Blood & Honey''.\n\nThe song is referenced in the lyrics of the [[Mudvayne]] song \"Internal Primates Forever\" on ''[[L.D. 50 (album)|L.D. 50]]''.\n\n[[Stone Sour]] also covered this song on their 2001 demo CD, giving it the name \"Death Dance of the Frog Fish\", and has also used it as exit music while on tour.\n\nSwedish death industrialists [[Brighter Death Now]] included a version of the song on their 2005 recording ''[[Kamikaze Kabaret]]''.\n\nGerman industrial/EBM act [[Neuroticfish]] covered the song on ''[[Gelb (album)|Gelb]]'' in 2005.\n\nA new version by Napoleon's Ghost was produced by [[Les Fradkin]] in 2006.  The flip or B-side of the single was recreated as well by Napoleon's Ghost \"!AaaH-aH ,yawA eM ekaT oT gnimoC er'yehT\".\n\nThe russian psytrance artist [[Psykovsky]] sampled parts of the song on his piece \"Badinerie Dreaming\", released on his album \"Na Ve Ka\" from 2011.\n\n[[Ray Stevens]] covered the song in 2012 for his nine-CD ''Encyclopedia of Recorded Comedy Music'' collection, complete with vocal speed changes, a drum beat, sirens, and a funny sped-up laugh.\n\n[[Butcher Babies]] covered the song on their EP ''Uncovered'' in 2014.\n\nThe 2018 [[Kids See Ghosts]] song \"[[Fire (Kids See Ghosts song)|Fire]]\" samples the percussion intro of the recording.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:They're Coming To Take Me Away, Ha-Haaa!}}\n[[Category:Debut singles]]\n[[Category:1966 singles]]\n[[Category:Novelty songs]]\n[[Category:Songs about dogs]]\n[[Category:Warner Records singles]]\n[[Category:1966 songs]]\n[[Category:Mental illness in fiction]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = They're Coming to Take Me Away, Ha-Haaa!\n| cover      = TheyreComingToTakeMeAway-singlecover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = Cover of the Rhino Records co. re-issue of the WB album\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Napoleon XIV]]\n| album      =\n| B-side     = !aaaH-aH ,yawA eM ekaT oT gnimoC er'yehT\n| released   = July 1966\n| format     = [[Gramophone record|7-inch single]]\n| recorded   = 1966\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Novelty song|Novelty]], [[Comedy music|comedy]]\n| length     = 2:10\n| label      = [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]] #5831\n| writer     = N. Bonaparte ([[Jerry Samuels]])\n| producer   = A Jepalana Production\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = I'm in Love with My Little Red Tricycle\n| next_year  = 1966\n| misc       = {{Extra album cover\n | header  = B-side\n | type    = single\n | cover   = Napoleon Xiv B side Original Issue.jpg\n | border  =\n | alt     =\n | caption = Label of the original 7-inch issue\n}}\n}}\n\n'''They're Coming to Take Me Away, Ha-Haaa!''' is a 1966 [[Novelty song|novelty]] record written and performed by Jerry Samuels (billed as [[Napoleon XIV]]), and released on [[Warner Bros. Records]]. The song became an instant success in the United States, peaking at No. 3 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] popular music singles chart on August 13<ref>[[Joel Whitburn]], ''The Billboard Book of Top 40 Hits'', Billboard Publications, 1983.</ref>, No. 1 on the [[Cash Box Top 100]] charts, No. 2 in Canada, and reaching No. 4 on the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref>''Joel Whitburn's Top Pop Singles 1955-1990'' - {{ISBN|0-89820-089-X}}</ref>\n\n== Lyrics ==\nThe lyrics appear to describe a man's mental anguish after a break-up with a woman, and his descent into madness leading to his committal to a \"funny farm\" (slang for a [[psychiatric hospital|mental hospital]]). It\u2019s finally revealed in last line of the third verse that he\u2019s not being driven insane by the loss of a woman \u2014 but by a runaway dog: \"They'll find you yet and when they do, they'll put you in the [[American Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals|ASPCA]], you mangy mutt\". According to Samuels, he was concerned the record could be seen as making fun of the mentally ill, and intentionally added that line so \"you realize that the person is talking about a dog having left him, not a human\". Said Samuels, \"I felt it would cause some people to say 'Well, it's alright.' And it did. It worked.\"<ref name=\"Crouse2000\">{{cite book|author=Richard Crouse|title=Big Bang, Baby: Rock Trivia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dYFv3ifE0f4C&pg=PA91|date=26 April 2000|publisher=Dundurn|isbn=978-0-88882-219-2|pages=91\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Crouse2012\">{{cite book|author=Richard Crouse|title=Who Wrote The Book Of Love?|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OyZyWKcmRhEC&pg=PT70|date=15 March 2012|publisher=Doubleday Canada|isbn=978-0-385-67442-3|pages=70\u2013}}</ref>\n\n== Song structure ==\nThe song is driven by a [[snare drum]], [[tambourine]] and hand clap rhythm. The vocal is spoken rhythmically rather than sung melodically, while the vocal pitch rises and falls at key points to create an unusual [[glissando]] effect, augmented by the sound of wailing sirens.<ref name=\"Crouse2012\" /><ref name=\"SF1\" /> \n\n== Technical background ==\nAccording to Samuels, the vocal glissando was achieved by manipulating the recording speed of his vocal track, a multitrack variation on the technique used by [[Ross Bagdasarian, Sr.|Ross Bagdasarian]] in creating the original [[The Chipmunks|Chipmunks]] novelty songs.<ref name=\"Crouse2012\" /> At the time the song was written, Samuels was working as a recording engineer at Associated Recording Studios in New York. Samuels discovered he could use a [[Variable Frequency Oscillator]] to alter the 60[[Hz]] [[Utility frequency|frequency]] of the [[Synchronous_motor#Hysteresis_motors|hysteresis motor]] of a [[Multitrack recording|multitrack]] tape recording machine in order to raise or lower the pitch of a voice without changing the tempo. This gave him the idea for a song based on the rhythm of the old Scottish tune \"[[The Campbells Are Coming]]\". After recording a percussion track at the standard speed, he played it back through headphones while recording the vocal on another track and gradually adjusting the VFO and the pace of his vocals to produce the desired effect. Some tracks were treated with intermittent tape-based echo effects created by an [[Echoplex]]. Samuels also layered in siren effects that gradually rose and fell with the pitch of his vocals.<ref name=\"Everett2008\">{{cite book|author=Walter Everett|title=The Foundations of Rock: From \"Blue Suede Shoes\" to \"Suite: Judy Blue Eyes\"|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P3NMCAAAQBAJ&pg=PT485|date=9 December 2008|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-029497-7|pages=485\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"SF1\">{{cite web |title=They're Coming To Take Me Away, Ha-haaa by Napoleon XIV |url=https://www.songfacts.com/facts/napoleon-xiv/theyre-coming-to-take-me-away-ha-haaa |website=SongFacts.com |publisher=SongFacts |accessdate=17 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n== B-side ==\nContinuing the theme of insanity, the flip or [[B-side]] of the single was simply the A-side [[backmasking|played in reverse]], and given the title \"!aaaH-aH ,yawA eM ekaT oT gnimoC er'yehT\" (or \"<span style=\"transform: scaleX(-1); display: inline-block;\">Ha-Haaa!</span> <span style=\"transform: scaleX(-1); display: inline-block;\">Away,</span> <span style=\"transform: scaleX(-1); display: inline-block;\">Me</span> <span style=\"transform: scaleX(-1); display: inline-block;\">Take</span> <span style=\"transform: scaleX(-1); display: inline-block;\">to</span> <span style=\"transform: scaleX(-1); display: inline-block;\">Coming</span> <span style=\"transform: scaleX(-1); display: inline-block;\">They're</span>\") and the performer billed as \"<span style=\"transform: scaleX(-1); display: inline-block;\">XIV</span> <span style=\"transform: scaleX(-1); display: inline-block;\">NAPOLEON</span>\". Most of the label affixed to the B-side was a mirror image of the front label (as opposed to simply being spelled backward), including the letters in the \"WB\" shield logo. Only the label name, disclaimer, and record and recording master numbers were kept frontward. The reverse version of the song is not included on the original Warner Bros. album, although the title is shown on the front cover, whereas the title is actually spelled backward.<ref name=\"Simpson2003\">{{cite book|author=Paul Simpson|title=The Rough Guide to Cult Pop|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=F7hpXcrqA-8C&pg=PA23|year=2003|publisher=Rough Guides|isbn=978-1-84353-229-3|pages=23\u2013}}</ref>\n\nIn his ''Book of Rock Lists'', rock music critic [[Dave Marsh]] calls the B-side the \"most obnoxious song ever to appear in a [[jukebox]]\", saying the recording once \"cleared out a [[diner]] of forty patrons in three minutes flat.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=The Book of Rock Lists|first=Dave|last=Marsh|first2=Kevin|last2=Stein|publisher=Dell Publishing|year=1981|p=[https://archive.org/details/bookofrocklists00mars/page/80 80]|isbn=978-0-440-57580-1|url=https://archive.org/details/bookofrocklists00mars/page/80}}</ref>\n\n== Airplay ==\nThe song charted at No. 3 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] charts on August 13<ref>[[Joel Whitburn]], ''The Billboard Book of Top 40 Hits'', Billboard Publications, 1983.</ref>, No. 1 on the [[Cash Box Top 100]] charts on July 30, No. 2 in Canada, and reaching No. 4 on the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref>''Joel Whitburn's Top Pop Singles 1955-1990'' - {{ISBN|0-89820-089-X}}</ref>\n\nWithin weeks of its release, [[WABC (AM)|WABC]] and [[WMCA (AM)|WMCA]] stopped playing the song in response to complaints about its content from mental health professionals and organizations.<ref name=\"SF2\">{{cite web |title=They're Coming To Take Me Away, Ha-Haaa! Napoleon XIV |url=https://www.songfacts.com/image/napoleon-xiv/theyre-coming-to-take-me-away-ha-haaa |website=Songfacts.com |publisher=Songfacts |accessdate=18 June 2019}}</ref> The [[BBC]] also refused to play the song.\n\nWarner Bros. Records reissued the original single (#7726) in 1973. It entered the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] at No. 87 but stalled at No. 101 at the Week Ahead charts which was an addition to the [[Cash Box Top 100]] charts. The reissue featured the \"Burbank/palm trees\" label.  As with the original release, the labels for the reissue's B-side also included mirror-imaged print except for the disclaimer, record catalog, and track master numbers.  The \"Burbank\" motto at the top of the label was also kept frontward as well as the \"WB\" letters in the shield logo, which had been printed in reverse on the originals.<ref name=\"Collins1998\">{{cite book|author=Ace Collins|title=Disco Duck and Other Adventures in Novelty Music|url=https://archive.org/details/discoduckotherad0000coll|url-access=registration|year=1998|publisher=Berkley Boulevard Books|isbn=978-0-425-16358-0|pages=[https://archive.org/details/discoduckotherad0000coll/page/210 210]\u2013211}}</ref>\n\n==Chart history==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1966)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])<ref>[http://www.poparchives.com.au/gosetcharts/1966/19661005.html Go-Set National Top 40, 5 October 1966]</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|40\n|-\n|Canada ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'' Top Singles<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/item.aspx?IdNumber=4323&|title=Item Display - RPM - Library and Archives Canada |website=Collectionscanada.gc.ca |date=1966-08-15 |accessdate=2018-08-16}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n|[[UK Singles Chart|UK]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/12632/napoleon-xiv/ |title=Official Charts Company |website=Officialcharts.com |date=1966-08-10 |accessdate=2018-08-16}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n|-\n|U.S. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]] <ref>''Joel Whitburn's Top Pop Singles 1955-1990'' - {{ISBN|0-89820-089-X}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n|U.S. [[Cash Box (magazine)|''Cash Box'']] Top 100<ref>[http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/60s_files/19660730.html Cash Box Top 100 Singles, July 30, 1966]</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|-\n|}\n\n==Sequels==\n\"I'm Happy They Took You Away, Ha-Haaa!\" was recorded by [[CBS Radio Mystery Theater]] cast member Bryna Raeburn, credited as \"Josephine XV\", and was the closing track on Side Two of the 1966 Warner Bros. album.  ([[Jos\u00e9phine de Beauharnais|Josephine]] was the name of the spouse of the French Emperor [[Napoleon Bonaparte]].)\n\nA variation of \"They're Coming to Take Me Away, Ha-Haaa!\" was also done by Jerry Samuels, from that same album entitled ''Where the Nuts hunt the Squirrels'', where Samuels, towards the end of the track, repeats the line: \"THEY'RE TRYING TO DRIVE ME SANE!!! HA HA,\" before the song's fade, in a fast-tracked higher voice.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.guitarcenter.com/M-Audio/Fast-Track-MKII-USB-Audio-Interface-1274115051782.gc |title=M-Audio Fast Track MKII USB Audio Interface |publisher=Guitar Center |date=2011-12-29 |accessdate=2016-09-29}}</ref>\n\nIn 1966, [[KRDC (AM)|KRLA]] [[DJ]] [[Hudson & Landry|\"Emperor Bob\" Hudson]] recorded a similarly styled song titled ''I'm Normal'', including the lines \"They came and took my brother away/The men in white picked him up yesterday/But they'll never come take me away, 'cos I'm O.K./I'm normal.\" Another line in the song was: \"I eat my peas with a tuning fork.\" The record was credited simply to \"The Emperor.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kfxm.com/EmperorHudson.htm |title=Emperor Hudson |website=Kfxm.com |date= |accessdate=2016-09-29}}</ref>\n\nIn 1988, Samuels wrote and recorded \"They're Coming To Get Me Again, Ha Haaa!\", a sequel to the original record. It was included on a single two years later on the ''Collectables'' label. Recorded with the same beat as the original, and portraying Napoleon XIV relapsing to madness after being released from an [[insane asylum]], it never charted, and was combined with the original 1966 recording on side A. (Both sequels are included on Samuels' 1996 ''Second Coming'' album.) In the song, instead of a \"mangy mutt,\" for his lost dog, Napoleon bemoans the loss of his pet monkey. (\"I'll swing you by your tail, you hairy ape!\") In the song, instead of the \"funny farm\" and the \"happy home\" Napoleon XIV is being taken away to the \"loony bin\" and the \"rubber room.\" Towards the end of the song, he relapses into the \"funny farm\" and \"happy home\"\u2014until when reality sinks in, he cries out at a fast tracked double voice with the words: \"OH NO!!!\" before the beat ends with a door slam, indicating that he has been locked up in the insane asylum.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfxsource.com/sound-effects/door-sound-effects/door-slam-sound-effects.html |title=Door Slam Sound Effects, Door Slam Sounds, Door Slam Sound Effect, Door Slam Sound Clips |website=Sfxsource.com |date= |accessdate=2016-09-29}}</ref>\n\nThe recording appeared on disk releases by [[Dr. Demento]] in 1975 as part of ''Dr. Demento's Delights'',<ref name=\"Inc.1975\">\"Billboard's Recommended LPs\". {{cite book|author=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|title=Billboard|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=exEEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA72|date=15 November 1975|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|pages=72\u2013|issn=0006-2510}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Newsweek|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uaoeAQAAMAAJ|date=October 1975|publisher=Newsweek, Incorporated|page=86}}</ref> then in subsequent Dr. Demento LP records released in 1985, 1988 and 1991.\n\n== Cover versions ==\n[[Kim Fowley]] released a cover of the song as his second single, after \"The Trip\".<ref name=\"Larkin2011\">{{cite book|author=Colin Larkin|title=The Encyclopedia of Popular Music|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_NNmFiUnSmUC&pg=PA2178|date=27 May 2011|publisher=Omnibus Press|isbn=978-0-85712-595-8|pages=2178\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Inc.1966\">\"International news reports\". {{cite book|author=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|title=Billboard|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EREEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA55|date=20 August 1966|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|pages=55\u2013|issn=0006-2510}}</ref>\n\nIn the UK a cover version was also released in November 1966 by the humorous pop group [[The Barron Knights]] where it was included on the B-side of their single \"Under New Management\".<ref>{{cite web|title=The Barron-Knights \u2013 Under New Management|url=http://www.45cat.com/record/db8071|website=45cat |accessdate=5 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[The Monkees]]' song \"Gonna Buy Me a Dog\", sung by [[Micky Dolenz]], features [[Davy Jones (actor)|Davy Jones]] teasing Dolenz toward the fade of the song with the words \"they're coming to take us away\" taken from Napoleon XIV's song.\n\nIn Argentina Pedro ''Pelusa'' Suero (a well known actor, announcer, and voice over) recorded, as \"Napole\u00f3n Puppy\", a cover in Spanish of this song titled \"Ellos me quieren llevar\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Napoleon Puppy \u2013 Discography|url=http://www.discogs.com/Napoleon-Puppy-Ellos-Me-Quieren-Llevar-Trisagio-Del-Soltero/release/6010916|website=Discogs |accessdate=17 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Jeff Duff]], as \"Cyril Trotts\", covered \"They're Coming To Take Me Away, Ha! Ha!\" in 1984 on his ''To Bogna'' LP.\n\nExperimental music band [[Nurse With Wound]] used some of the lyrics from the song for their limited 7\" release \"No Hiding from the Blackbird/Burial Of The Sardine\".\n\n[[Biz Markie]] also covers this song on ''[[Make the Music with Your Mouth, Biz]]'' in 1986, but he changes most of the lyrics.\n\n[[Austen Tayshus]] covered the song on his 1988 album ''Whispering Joke'' and also as a single. The B-side (a reversed version) was recreated as well.\n\n[[Jello Biafra]] covered this song with his band [[Lard (band)|Lard]] on their album ''[[The Last Temptation of Reid]]'' in 1990.\n\nIn 1998, [[Amanda Lear]] included this song in her compilation ''Made in Blood & Honey''.\n\nThe song is referenced in the lyrics of the [[Mudvayne]] song \"Internal Primates Forever\" on ''[[L.D. 50 (album)|L.D. 50]]''.\n\n[[Stone Sour]] also covered this song on their 2001 demo CD, giving it the name \"Death Dance of the Frog Fish\", and has also used it as exit music while on tour.\n\nSwedish death industrialists [[Brighter Death Now]] included a version of the song on their 2005 recording ''[[Kamikaze Kabaret]]''.\n\nGerman industrial/EBM act [[Neuroticfish]] covered the song on ''[[Gelb (album)|Gelb]]'' in 2005.\n\nA new version by Napoleon's Ghost was produced by [[Les Fradkin]] in 2006.  The flip or B-side of the single was recreated as well by Napoleon's Ghost \"!AaaH-aH ,yawA eM ekaT oT gnimoC er'yehT\".\n\nThe russian psytrance artist [[Psykovsky]] sampled parts of the song on his piece \"Badinerie Dreaming\", released on his album \"Na Ve Ka\" from 2011.\n\n[[Ray Stevens]] covered the song in 2012 for his nine-CD ''Encyclopedia of Recorded Comedy Music'' collection, complete with vocal speed changes, a drum beat, sirens, and a funny sped-up laugh.\n\n[[Butcher Babies]] covered the song on their EP ''Uncovered'' in 2014.\n\nThe 2018 [[Kids See Ghosts]] song \"[[Fire (Kids See Ghosts song)|Fire]]\" samples the percussion intro of the recording.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:They're Coming To Take Me Away, Ha-Haaa!}}\n[[Category:Debut singles]]\n[[Category:1966 singles]]\n[[Category:Novelty songs]]\n[[Category:Songs about dogs]]\n[[Category:Warner Records singles]]\n[